title: For Sale:  AK-103 Arsenal SLR-107
postcontent:
I need money right now so I'm selling my AK-103, Arsenal SLR-107.
It is my firm belief that rifles like this will some day be banned, not if, but when, especially ones that are imported.
The AK-103 style folding stock is only imported by Arsenal. You can interchange it with the polymer AK-103 folding stock ($200, not included).
Both are indistinguishable from a solid stock in terms of handling and very compact. It makes a loud bang when unfolding, just to give you an idea.

Unfired and comes with 3 Circle 10 magazines and 500 rounds of brown bear lacquer.
It comes with stainless steel heatshield and polymer handguard, 90 degrees gas block and double crescent muzzle brake.
It is an AK-103 in all aspect except not full auto.

I'm asking for $1050.
That's not a bargain but it's a damn good deal.

An identical rifle at Arsenal right now is $859. That is the polymer version, my version with the steel stock has been out-of-stock for months.
You add in FFL fees + 3 Circle10 magazines ($30 each)+ 500 rounds of brown bear, and it's a pretty good deal, considering that it is unfired. 
The barrel is also hammer-forged, chrome-lined.

I have never fired it so I do not know the accuracy, but the certification sheet of the 3 test shots at the factory indicate around 2 MOA.

title: For Trade:  Two nice old rifles, Arisaka 38 "with mum" and a Flobert.
postcontent:
Up for trade are two nice rifles, one is a Arisaka type 38 6.5x50 with intact "mum" that has been stamped over with the school mark, school training rifle. and the other is a Flobert falling breech .32. Below is information that I have found on both rifles. The Flobert is complete and in great condition, the Arisaka is missing the magazine "still available", and is also in great condition. I have several other pictures of both guns, just contact me with your email adress and i will send whatever pictures you need. I also have a brand new Harris bipod listed in the acessories section. Would like to trade for another firearm item.

Flobert: During the period from the 1890s through about 1920 "Boy's rifles" were very popular items for youngsters. Belgium was a major source of inexpensive guns, and many thousands were imported, often sold by big mail order companies like Sears, Montgomery Wards, etc.  The most common action used was a "Flobert" design; this is similar to what Americans often call a "rolling block" action. Most Flobert rifles were .22 rim fire (sometimes short, or long, or long rifle).  Sometimes other caliber's are seen, .25 or .32 rim fire, or even 9mm rim fire.  

Arisaka Type 38 School Training Rifle 6.5X50: At various times, rifles were removed from military service and sold to other countries or transferred to Japanese schools as training weapons. Normally, the chrysanthemum on these rifles was over stamped with the Koishikawa (Tokyo) / Kokura Arsenal symbol or a ring of small circles to indicate that the rifle no longer belonged to the Imperial Japanese Army. Rifles given to schools often have an additional character stamped on the top of the receiver between the chrysanthemum and the type designation characters. Most of these "school-marked" rifles also have two or three zeros preceding the serial number.

SKS rifle (not the carbine), Chinese manufacture, Norinco type 56. In good condition, shows some minor finish wear, nothing you wouldn't expect from a weapon of this age.

This is a Century imported Romanian made (Cugir factory) PSL 54c.  Also known as the ROMAK III...and also known as the Romanian Dragunov. The POSP type optic has very good glass, an excellent combat reticle, fine adjustments, and it slides on and off the rifle base effortlessly but stays put under fire.

title: For Sale:  500 Rounds of Speer Frangible ammo--40 S&W
postcontent:
The ammo is good for steel plinking, up close training, and cleaner for indoor range usage. 
website description:
This is 40 S&W Speer Lawman Clean Fire 125gr. Reduced Hazard Taining (RHT) Frangible Ammo. For clean, close-up training, you need a lead-free bullet that crumbles into very small pieces when it hits a metal backstop. Lawman RHT ammunition features a precision-formed bullet made of sintered copper, which is powdered copper that's compressed under heat and pressure to form a bullet. Sintered technology means there's no separate jacket that can produce sharp fragments on impact with a steel backstop. The tip of each RHT bullet is distinctively marked so range officers can easily tell it from conventional ammunition. You also need a primer that's free of lead, barium and antimony. This ammo has that covered with the CCI Clean-Fire primer. Clean-Fire priming not only eliminates the heavy metals found in conventional primers but also leaves very little residue in the shellcase and firearm, which results in shooters and their equipment stay cleaner. Lawman RHT Ammunition is the right choice for improving air quality in indoor training ranges, or for ranges where bullet bounce-back has proved to be a problem. Use RHT for clean and close realistic training and practice.

title: For Sale:  Body Armor Vest
postcontent:
Up for sale is my woodland camo PASGT body armor protective vest. It is a medium (chest 37 to 41 inches), but seems to run larger (I am 6'3" 208lbs.). It is in good condition an comes with a desert camo cover to accommodate different environments. I am looking for $150 obo. Please let me know if you have any questions. 

Here is some background information on the vest:

The Personnel Armor System for Ground Troops Vest, also known as the "flak vest", was the United States Military's standard upper torso body armor from the early 1980s until approximately 2004, when it was replaced by the Interceptor body armor. The PASGT Vest replaced the Vietnam War-era M-69 Fragmentation Protective Body Armor nylon vest, which in turn replaced the Korean War-era M-1952A Fragmentation Protective Body Armor. The PASGT Vest used Kevlar for the first time in the United States military's body armor, unlike the ballistic nylon used in the previous two models. While incapable of stopping rifle bullets, the PASGT Vest provided better protection against shrapnel and reduced the severity of injuries from small arms fire when compared to the M-69. Anecdotally, it provides roughly level IIIA ballistic protection, not accounting for blunt force injuries, stopping rounds as powerful as a .44 magnum from a handgun[2] in certain test methodologies.  The PASGT Vest weighed approximately 9 pounds, a small increase over the previous model.

In order to provide protection against high velocity bullets, the PASGT Vest was, in 1996, combined with the Interim Small Arms Protective Overvest (ISAPO) pending adoption of Interceptor body armor. The ISAPO weighed about 16.5 pounds and consisted of a carrier to hold two protective ceramic plate inserts. A PASGT armor system with overvest weighed more than 25 pounds and was criticized by many US troops as unacceptably cumbersome in combat. The ballistic fill consists of 13 plies of 14 oz. water repellent treated Aramid (Kevlar 29) fabric. The inner and outer cover, shoulder pads and front closure flap of the vest are water repellent treated 8 oz. ballistic nylon cloth. While phased out as frontline body armor by the time of the 2003 Iraq War, some Army units would use old PASGT Vests as makeshift armor for their vehicles in the absence of purpose-made up-armor kits.

title: For Sale:  .45 ACP Taurus 24/7 PRO DS  12+1
postcontent:
This is a 6 month old Taurus PT24/7 PRO DS in .45 ACP. It has about 300 rounds through it. Finish is about 97% as it has some mild barrel smileys and the slide has a little holster wear. It took about 150 rounds to break in the magazines which weren't feeding some hollow points at first (common problem with many taurus semi-autos). The first four rounds didn't feed properly. The magazines now feed most hollow points. FMJ ammo has always fed perfectly. This gun has a polished feed ramp from the factory which is nice. Taurus also provides a life long guarantee on the gun. In fact, I already used it to get a free guide rod/spring because the initial one had some corrosion on it. I was going to get replacement magazines too but I got the 3 I had working good. They are pretty good to deal with.

I carried this hiking and around town both concealed and in a SERPA holster also for sale with it. I'm upgrading to a magnum gun for bears (yep, had a black bear encounter last weekend camping and learned my .45 would not have done much) and need to sell this. I've had several .45 polymer guns and oddly enough, this inexpensive little Taurus is much more comfortable and a better recoil manager. Yes, I know that doesn't sound likely, but it's got a smaller and much more ergonomic grip (it's like a .40 sized grip, not a .45), and it handles recoil easier than the glock 21sf and M&P45 I had. It is also a very good looking gun. I enjoyed carrying it concealed and OWB with 12+1 rounds and recommend it over the heavier, larger glock 21.  One other cool feature of this gun is that it's not just a SA/DA striker fired gun, it's SA option will go to DA if the striker falls on a bad primer or hard primer.  Pretty cool feature, and the SA pull is very light and crisp, the DA pull is long and safe.  Oh yeah, the manual safety also decocks the striker when pushed all the way up.  Find these features on ANY other .45 gun, if it exists, then find it for under $400!

For $325 you get the gun, 3 magazines that hold 12 rounds each, and the hard case with cleaning brush and mag loader. I paid $385 for it 6 months ago so I figure $325 is more than fair.

For $425 you'll also get 320 rounds (170+ are 230grain FMJs, 150+ are assorted 230grain JHPs) AND a blackhawk SERPA holster with both the paddle attachment and the belt attachment. The ammo and holster are at least $150 worth of stuff, I'm bundling them with the gun for only $100.

I'd prefer a face to face transaction. Contact me with any questions.
